.TH "TEMPORAL.INSTANT.SUBTRACT" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.Instant.subtract \- Temporal.Instant.prototype.subtract()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]subtract()\f[B]\f[R] method of
\f[CR]Temporal.Instant\f[R] instances returns a new
\f[CR]Temporal.Instant\f[R] object representing this instant moved
backward by a given duration (in a form convertible by
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration.from()\f[R]).
.PP
If you want to subtract two instants and get a duration, use
\f[CR]since()\f[R] or \f[CR]until()\f[R] instead.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
subtract(duration)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]duration\f[R]
A string, an object, or a \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] instance
representing a duration to subtract from this instant.
It is converted to a \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object using the same
algorithm as \f[CR]Temporal.Duration.from()\f[R].
.SS Return value
A new \f[CR]Temporal.Instant\f[R] object representing subtracting
\f[CR]duration\f[R] from this instant.
If \f[CR]duration\f[R] is positive, then the returned instant is earlier
than this instant; if \f[CR]duration\f[R] is negative, then the returned
instant is later than this instant.
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]RangeError\f[R]
Thrown in one of the following cases:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]duration\f[R] is a calendar duration (it has a non\-zero
\f[CR]years\f[R], \f[CR]months\f[R], or \f[CR]weeks\f[R]), or has a
non\-zero \f[CR]days\f[R], because calendar durations are ambiguous
without a calendar and time reference.
.IP \(bu 2
The result is not in the representable range, which is ±10\(ha8 days, or
about ±273,972.6 years, from the Unix epoch.
.RE
.SH DESCRIPTION
Subtracting a duration is equivalent to adding its negation, so all the
same considerations apply.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Subtracting a Temporal.Duration
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] instant = Temporal.Instant.fromEpochMilliseconds(1000);
\f[B]const\f[R] duration = Temporal.Duration.from(\(dqPT1S\(dq); \f[I]// One\-second duration\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] newInstant = instant.subtract(duration);
console.log(newInstant.epochMilliseconds); \f[I]// 0\f[R]
.EE
.PP
For more examples, see \f[CR]add()\f[R].
